Part 1: EDA and Model Selection¶

Introduction¶

This report is the first part of final assessment for Swinburne University of Technology, COS80023 Big Data. This report embarks on a journey starting from data preprocessing, where the data is cleansed and prepared for analysis, followed by exploratory data analysis to uncover underlying structures and relationships. Hypothesis tests are conducted to validate assumptions about diamond prices based on their characteristics. Subsequently, the report delves into machine learning to predict diamond prices, employing models such as Linear Regression, XGBoost, and Random Forest. The performance of these models is meticulously evaluated to ensure the reliability of the predictions.

The detail of the second part (Model Deployment) will be detailed in the Report and Github (Link will be provided at the end of the Notebook).

Source: Vrai

Clarity represents the clarity grades of diamonds in the dataset, ranging from included (SI1, SI2), very slightly included (VS1, VS2), very very slightly included (VVS1, VVS2), to the rarest and most pure forms, internally flawless (IF) and flawless (FL). These grades indicate the level of imperfections or inclusions in the diamonds, with FL being completely free of inclusions even under 10x magnification, and SI grades containing inclusions that are noticeable under magnification. These clarity levels are critical for evaluating diamond quality and value.

In [ ]:
diamonds_df['report'].unique()
Out[ ]:
array(['GIA', 'HRD', 'IGI', 'GCAL'], dtype=object)
  • GIA: Gemological Institute of America, known for its strict grading standards.
  • HRD: Hoge Raad voor Diamant (Diamond High Council), based in Antwerp, known for high-quality diamond certification.
  • IGI: International Gemological Institute, provides a wide range of services including grading for diamonds of all sizes.
  • GCAL: Gem Certification and Assurance Lab, known for its guarantee on diamond grading. Each report provides a professional assessment of the diamonds' characteristics such as cut, color, clarity, and carat weight.
In [ ]:
diamonds_df['type'].unique()
Out[ ]:
array(['natural', 'lab'], dtype=object)

Source: JPratt Designs

Type represents two categories of diamonds included in the dataset: 'natural' and 'lab'.

  • Natural diamonds are those formed over billions of years in the Earth's mantle under natural geological processes.
  • Lab-created, or synthetic, diamonds are grown in controlled laboratory environments using technological processes that replicate the conditions under which natural diamonds develop.

Both types of diamonds possess identical chemical and physical properties, but their origins are distinctly different.

Hypothesis Testing¶

1, The average price of round shape diamonds vs all shape diamonds¶

Null Hypothesis (H0): All shape and type have same average price

In [ ]:
# Create separate DataFrames for each type of diamonds
all_types_df = diamonds_df
natural_df = diamonds_df[diamonds_df['type'] == 'natural']
lab_df = diamonds_df[diamonds_df['type'] == 'lab']
In [ ]:
def compare_average_prices(df, type_label):
    # Group by 'cut' and calculate the mean price for each group
    average_price_by_cut = df.groupby('shape')['price'].mean()
    # Perform a t-test between the group of 'Round' cut diamonds and all other cuts
    round_prices = df[df['shape'] == 'Round']['price']
    other_prices = df[df['shape'] != 'Round']['price']
    t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(round_prices, other_prices, equal_var=False, nan_policy='omit')
    # Sort the average prices from highest to lowest
    sorted_average_prices = average_price_by_cut.sort_values(ascending=False)
    # Print the results
    print(f"{type_label} - t-statistic: {t_stat}, p-value: {p_value}")
    print(f"{type_label} - Average prices from highest to lowest:")
    print(sorted_average_prices)

Machine Learning¶

1, Preprocessing¶

a, Remove outlier¶

In [ ]:
# Define the conditions for rows to be removed
conditions = (diamonds_df['carat'] > 8) | (diamonds_df['price'] > 30000)

# Filter out the rows that meet the conditions
diamonds_df = diamonds_df[~conditions]

Diamonds exceeding 8 carats were considered outliers due to their rarity and the significant impact they have on the overall price distribution. Similarly, diamonds priced over $30,000 were removed as they represent a segment of the market that is not typical of the average consumer experience and could skew the analysis towards these high-value transactions.

b, Split data for train/test¶

In [ ]:
# Split the dataset into training and testing sets
train_df, test_df = train_test_split(diamonds_df, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
# Separate the target variable 'price' from the features
X_train = train_df.drop(columns='price')
y_train = train_df['price']
X_test = test_df.drop(columns='price')
y_test = test_df['price']
X_train.shape, X_test.shape

c, Transform the dataset to fit model¶

In [ ]:
# Define the columns to be encoded and scaled
categorical_features = ['shape', 'cut', 'color', 'clarity', 'report', 'type']
numerical_features = ['carat']
# Create a column transformer
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', StandardScaler(), numerical_features),
        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(drop='first'), categorical_features)
    ])
# Fit the preprocessor on the training data and transform both training and testing data
X_train_preprocessed = preprocessor.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_preprocessed = preprocessor.transform(X_test)
X_train_preprocessed.shape, X_test_preprocessed.shape

2, Linear Regression Model¶

a, Train model¶

In [ ]:
# Initialize and train the linear regression model
lr_model = LinearRegression()
lr_model.fit(X_train_preprocessed, y_train)
# Predict on the testing set
y_pred = lr_model.predict(X_test_preprocessed)
# Calculate performance metrics
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
rmse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred, squared=False)  # squared=False gives RMSE
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
mse, mae, rmse, r2

mse_rf = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_rf)
mae_rf = mean_absolute_error(y_test,y_pred_rf)
rmse_rf = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_rf, squared=False)
r2_rf = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_rf)
mse_rf, mae_rf, rmse_rf, r2_rf

The Random Forest model shows a high R-squared of 0.979, indicating it explains 97.9% of the variance in prices, with a low Mean Absolute Error of about 202.55, suggesting accurate predictions. A little bit better than XGB model.

4, Model Comparison¶

In [ ]:
mse_values = [mse, mse_xgb, mse_rf]
mae_values = [mae, mae_xgb, mae_rf]
rmse_values = [rmse, rmse_xgb, rmse_rf]
r2_values = [r2, r2_xgb, r2_rf]
model_names = ['Linear Regression', 'XGBoost', 'Random Forest']
def create_bar_chart(metric_values, metric_name, model_names):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    y_pos = np.arange(len(model_names))
    plt.bar(y_pos, metric_values, align='center', alpha=0.7)
    plt.xticks(y_pos, model_names)
    plt.ylabel(metric_name)
    plt.title(f'{metric_name} Comparison of Model Performance')
    for i in range(len(y_pos)):
        plt.text(x = y_pos[i]-0.15 , y = metric_values[i]+0.05, s = round(metric_values[i], 2), size = 10)
    plt.show()
# Create bar charts for each metric
create_bar_chart(mse_values, 'MSE', model_names)
create_bar_chart(mae_values, 'MAE', model_names)
create_bar_chart(rmse_values, 'RMSE', model_names)
create_bar_chart(r2_values, 'R2', model_names)
  • MSE Chart: Lower is better. Shows Random Forest with the lowest MSE, indicating the smallest difference on average between the predicted and actual values.
  • MAE Chart: Lower is better. Shows Random Forest with the lowest MAE, indicating more accurate predictions on average.
  • RMSE Chart: Lower is better. Random Forest again shows the lowest RMSE, suggesting it has the least variance in its error.
  • R Chart: Higher is better. Close to 1 is ideal. Both XGBoost and Random Forest models show very high R, indicating a strong ability to explain the variance in the data.

In conclusion, after evaluating the performance of Linear Regression, XGBoost, and Random Forest models through various metrics such as MSE, MAE, RMSE, and R, the Random Forest model emerged as the most effective for predicting diamond prices. With the lowest MSE and MAE and a high R value, it demonstrates superior accuracy and consistency. Consequently, the Random Forest model has been chosen for deployment due to its robust predictive capabilities and its potential to provide reliable price estimates in a production environment.
